│ Data->incrementUnscheduledDeps(-1) == 0) {\n```\n\nThe logic assumes that   │
│ if `IsControl` is true, we can safely call `incrementUnscheduledDeps()`     │
│ even when `hasValidDependencies()` is false. However, this is incorrect     │
│ because `incrementUnscheduledDeps()` has an assertion that requires         │
│ `hasValidDependencies()` to be true.\n\nThe issue is that control           │
│ dependencies can point to instructions that haven't had their dependencies  │
│ calculated yet (hence `hasValidDependencies()` returns false), but the code │
│ tries to modify their unscheduled dependency count anyway.\n\n4. Proposed   │
│ Edit Point(s):\n\nThe fix is to ensure that we only call                    │
│ `incrementUnscheduledDeps()` when the ScheduleData actually has valid       │
│ dependencies, even for control dependencies. The condition should be        │
│ modified to require `Data->hasValidDependencies()` regardless of whether    │
│ it's a control dependency or not.\n\n5. Conclusion:\n\nBy changing the      │
│ condition to require `Data->hasValidDependencies()` unconditionally, we     │
│ prevent the assertion failure. This is safe because if dependencies haven't │
│ been calculated yet, there's no meaningful unscheduled dependency count to  │
│ modify, and the instruction will be properly handled when its dependencies  │
│ are eventually calculated."                                                 │
│ }                                                                           │
